## Example 3: Suspicious Patterns Test (malicious.tree)

dangerous-project/
├── $(whoami)/                     # Command substitution
├── id/                         # Backtick command substitution
├── ../../../etc/                 # Directory traversal
├── /root/secrets/                # Absolute path
├── user*data/                    # Glob pattern
├── temp[0-9]/                    # Bracket pattern
├── logs|backup/                  # Pipe character
├── config;rm-rf/                 # Semicolon
├── data&&echo/                   # Command chaining
├── files>output/                 # Redirection
├── ${HOME}/.ssh/                 # Variable substitution
├── app<input/                    # Input redirection
├── test?.log                     # Question mark pattern
├── backup{1,2,3}/               # Brace expansion
├── data//extra/               # Multiple slashes
├── files\nmalicious/            # Newline character
├── config\x41\x42/              # Hex characters
├── temp\0null/                  # Null character
├── data\r\nwindows/             # Windows line endings
├── unicode\u0000/               # Unicode null
├── script.sh.exe                # Suspicious extension
├── payload.bat                  # Batch file
├── trojan.com                   # COM file
├── virus.pif                    # PIF file
└── malware.scr                  # Screen saver executable